t III: Formal and Practical Issues on the Lexicon of Greek: Morphology, Syntax and Semantics -- tRules for o-ablauting perfects in ancient grammatical treatises: reflections on Theodosius' Κανόνες / rBenedetti, Marina -- tConnective particles and literary units in Attic forensic speeches / rCrespo, Emilio -- tThe east/west and right/left dualism and the rise of some taboos in ancient Greek language and culture / rGiannakis, Georgios K. -- tThe Productivity of the suffix -σύνη from Homer to the present day, with special reference to the 'Septuagint' and New Testament / rJames, Patrick -- tOn some related προ-forms for generational distance in Modern Greek / rJoseph, Brian D. -- tExplanation of Homeric glosses in P. Cair. Mich. II 4 (Socrates archive)? / rPagani, Lara -- tGreek lexicography and the designation of helotic-like populations in Ancient Greece: The history of three compounds / rRuano, Paloma Guijarro / Vega, Maria Luisa del Barrio -- tLexicographical Scholia in ms. GA 1424 / rTosi, Renzo -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex  aThis volume presents nineteen studies by specialists in the field of Greek lexicography. A number of papers deal with historical aspects of Greek lexicography covering all phases of the language, i.e. ancient, medieval and modern, as well as the interrelations of Greek to neighboring languages. In addition, other papers address more formal issues, such as morphological, semantic and syntactic problems that are relevant to the study of Greek lexicography, as well as the study of individual words. Finally, in one study the problem of technical linguistic terminology is addressed along with the methodological, epistemological and other issues relating to the particular problem. The work is of special interest to scholars on the long standing problems of diachronic semantics, historical morphology and word formation, and to all those interested in etymology and the study of words of the Greek language.  aMode of access